Let the user filter for one or more verb groups.
Let the user filter for one or more sentence types.  
Let the CEFR level filter for everything else.

To make this work, your Logic Engine needs to treat the CEFR level as the Primary Filter that prunes your JSON schemas before the other filters even touch them.

The Multi-Filter Logic Flow
Here is how the data should flow through your engine:

1.  CEFR Filter (The "Everything Else"): Prunes available Tenses, Moods, and Negation types from the verb_functional_schema.
2.  Verb Group Filter: Prunes the verbs.json to only show, for example, "er_regular" and "full_irregulars".
3.  Sentence Type Filter: Selects the specific formula from sentence_schema.json (e.g., "intonation" or "est_ce_que").

Snippet:
// --- THE MASTER FILTER FUNCTION ---
function getPracticeSession(cefr, selectedGroups, selectedSentences) {
// 1. Filter Verbs by Group + CEFR (Must be at or below slider)
const availableVerbs = Object.keys(verbs).filter(v =>
selectedGroups.includes(verbs[v].group) &&
["A1", "A2", "B1", "B2"].indexOf(verbs[v].cefr) <= ["A1", "A2", "B1", "B2"].indexOf(cefr)
);

    // 2. Filter Tenses by CEFR
    const availableTenses = Object.keys(verb_functional_schema.tenses).filter(t =>
      verb_functional_schema.tenses[t].levels.includes(cefr)
    );

    // 3. Filter Sentence Types by Choice + CEFR
    const availableSentences = Object.keys(sentence_schema.interrogative_logic).filter(s =>
      selectedSentences.includes(s) &&
      sentence_schema.interrogative_logic[s].levels.includes(cefr)
    );

    return {
      verbs: availableVerbs,
      tenses: availableTenses,
      structures: availableSentences
    };

}
